sentence: Camille Lucie Nickerson (March 30, 1888 – April 27, 1982) was a pianist, composer, arranger, collector, and Howard University professor from 1926 to 1962.
She was influenced by Creole folksongs of Louisiana, which she arranged and sang.
Nickerson was born in the French Quarter of New Orleans, the daughter of music professor and band director William Joseph Nickerson and his first wife, Aurelie Duconge.

During the 1930s and into the 1950s she toured the United States as "The Louisiana Lady", singing creole songs and dressed in a series of ruffled gowns to evoke New Orleans history.
